<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1780,2023]" pageId="5" pageNumber="572">
Based on 
<specimenCount box="[263,385,1780,1806]" pageId="5" pageNumber="572" type="female">16 females</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[441,528,1780,1806]" pageId="5" pageNumber="572" type="male">8 males</specimenCount>
from 
<taxonomicName box="[598,788,1780,1806]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapotaceae" genus="Mimusops" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="572" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elengi">
<emphasis box="[598,788,1780,1806]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="572">Mimusops elengi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taken 
<date box="[865,985,1780,1806]" pageId="5" pageNumber="572" value="2020-03-11">
11.iii. 
<quantity box="[922,985,1780,1806]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.1308" pageId="5" pageNumber="572" unit="in" value="2020.0">2020</quantity>
</date>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[1022,1082,1780,1806]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="572">India</collectingCountry>
, Bengaluru, this species is here recorded from Western Australia and 
<collectingCountry box="[566,742,1816,1842]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="5" pageNumber="572">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
. This distribution seems remarkable but is not greatly different from that indicated above for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moulton" authorityYear="1940" box="[489,619,1852,1878]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Taeniothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="572" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatus">
<emphasis box="[489,619,1852,1878]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="572">L. fasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The specimens studied listed below agree fully with the recent detailed description of this species. It is probably closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[809,910,1888,1914]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Physothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="572" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lefroyi">
<emphasis box="[809,910,1888,1914]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="572">L. lefroyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but has the metascutum only weakly reticulate (cf 
<figureCitation box="[189,318,1924,1951]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–16" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1463,1487]" captionTargetBox="[155,1432,452,1439]" captionTargetId="figure-125@5.[151,1435,452,1439]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–16. Lefroyothrips species—metascutum. (11) fasciatus holotype; (12) fasciatus paratype male; (13) fasciatus male; (14) lefroyi; (15) tribulationi; (16) varatharajani." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543159/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="572">Figs 14, 16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="573" pageId="5" pageNumber="572" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1780,2023]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1437,151,429]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="573" pageId="5" pageNumber="572">
<emphasis box="[199,419,1960,1986]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="572">Female macroptera</emphasis>
. Body and legs yellow, posterior tergites brownish-yellow; antennal segments IV–VI brown or with brown marking (
<figureCitation box="[429,499,1996,2023]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-137@3.[151,1435,417,1909]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Lefroyothrips species. Antennal segments, 1–6: (1) fasciatus holotype; (2) fasciatus male; (3) lefroyi; (4) pictus paratype; (5) tribulationi; (6) varatharajani. 7–8 lefroyi: (7) female; (8) head &amp; pronotum. L. tribulationi, 9–10: (9) head; (10) pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543157" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543157/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="572">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); fore wings pale with two short shaded areas, at veinal fork and subapically. With the character states of the generic diagnosis. Ocellar setae pair III slightly shorter than distance between posterior ocelli (
<figureCitation box="[227,310,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–27" captionStartId="7.[151,264,808,832]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,783]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[151,1435,181,783]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 24–27. Lefroyothrips species. L. varatharajani 24–26: (24) head; (25) male tergites VIII–IX; (26) male sternites. (27) L. lefroyi male sternites." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543163" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543163/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="573">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
); postocular setae in single row with S2 sometimes slightly displaced posteriorly. Metascutum weakly reticulate (
<figureCitation box="[271,354,223,250]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–16" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1463,1487]" captionTargetBox="[155,1432,452,1439]" captionTargetId="figure-125@5.[151,1435,452,1439]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–16. Lefroyothrips species—metascutum. (11) fasciatus holotype; (12) fasciatus paratype male; (13) fasciatus male; (14) lefroyi; (15) tribulationi; (16) varatharajani." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543159/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="573">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
), CPS on posterior third of sclerite and slightly variable in position. Fore wing first vein distally with 1 or 2 setae. Sternite VII setae S2 arise at posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,429]" pageId="6" pageNumber="573">
<emphasis box="[199,394,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="573">Male macroptera</emphasis>
. Similar to female; tergite VIII with long comb, IX with 3 pairs of stout setae (
<figureCitation box="[1282,1366,294,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–27" captionStartId="7.[151,264,808,832]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,783]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[151,1435,181,783]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 24–27. Lefroyothrips species. L. varatharajani 24–26: (24) head; (25) male tergites VIII–IX; (26) male sternites. (27) L. lefroyi male sternites." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543163" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543163/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="573">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
); sternites III–VII with transverse pore plate close to anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[876,960,331,358]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–27" captionStartId="7.[151,264,808,832]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,783]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[151,1435,181,783]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 24–27. Lefroyothrips species. L. varatharajani 24–26: (24) head; (25) male tergites VIII–IX; (26) male sternites. (27) L. lefroyi male sternites." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543163" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543163/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="573">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
